	<div id="id1b58" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="Streetsblog writes about cars so we don’t have to  " width="565" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/62a495da"/><span class="title">Streetsblog writes about cars so we don’t have to  </span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>, <span>on December 17, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id1b59" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../../city/tag/drivers/#selected-tag"><span>drivers</span></a><span id="id1b5a">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/web/#selected-tag"><span>web</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p>God, what a relief! It seemed like the only pedestrian advocates out there were bunch of Internet-clueless organizations mostly interested in bicycles. <em>City slicking</em> was thinking, you know, that someone should produce a weblog entirely about pedestrian issues, and we&#8217;d do it ourselves, gosh, if we had the energy.</p>


	<h4><img src="/pictures/cars.jpg" alt="" /></h4>


	<p><a href="http://www.streetsblog.org/">Streetsblog</a> has the energy apparently. Damn, scrolling through the recent posts, it&#8217;s a candy store for curmudgeonly post-feminist ultra-post-environmentalist cave-dwelling hermits like Doctor Barnett. <a href="http://www.streetsblog.org/2006/12/14/are-old-line-environmentalists-asleep-at-the-wheel/">Are Old-Line Environmentalists Asleep at the Wheel?</a> Ha! Yes they totally are.</p>


	<p>I&#8217;m not sure why I&#8217;m using my sarcastic voice-altering device [<em>ed: jealous?</em>], because I am really excited about <em>Streetsblog</em>. It&#8217;s exactly the sort of Internet-driven groundswell of sanity I was hoping for. And so with newfound optimism, I lay out my predictions for the evolution of Manhattan streets:</p>


	<ul>
	<li>2008 – Congestion pricing in lower Manhattan.</li>
		<li>2009 – &#8220;Free&#8221; parking largely eliminated, some spots converted to centralized meters and others to wider sidewalks.</li>
		<li>2010 – Some streets (Prince) closed to regular automobiles entirely.</li>
	</ul>


	<p>I think these things will happen sooner or later and that if they are posponed by inept government, bottled up discontent will eventually explode into hard restrictions on which idiotic personal cars are allowed to enter the island at all.</p>


	<h4><a href="http://technically.us/doc/articles/2005/11/13/congestion-tax-the-best-we-can-hope-for">Pay up,</a> bitches, or don&#8217;t. Either way you won&#8217;t be permitted to run us down much longer.</h4></div>
	</div>
